          "body": "The chapter's closing movement (2:11-13) introduces Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite. They come from different regions, but their initial response is identical and right: they come 'to sympathize with him and comfort him' (*nacham*, 2:11). What they find when they arrive is so devastating that they cannot recognize Job at a distance (2:12). The man whose greatness was known throughout the East is now unrecognizable. They weep aloud, tear their robes, and throw dust over their heads toward the sky — all ancient expressions of solidarity with grief (cf. Genesis 37:34; Joshua 7:6; Lamentations 2:10). Then they sit down with him on the ground for seven days and seven nights, saying nothing — 'for they saw that his pain was very great' (2:13). This is the friends at their best. The silence is not passivity; it is the recognition that suffering of this magnitude exceeds the reach of words. The tragedy of the book is that they eventually break the silence with wrong speech. But in chapter 2, before theology intrudes, they do the most human and most faithful thing available: they stay."
